fields.name: majorDimension
fields.description:
The major dimension of the values.

For output, if the spreadsheet data is: `A1=1,B1=2,A2=3,B2=4`,
then requesting `range=A1:B2,majorDimension=ROWS` will return
`[[1,2],[3,4]]`,
whereas requesting `range=A1:B2,majorDimension=COLUMNS` will return
`[[1,3],[2,4]]`.

For input, with `range=A1:B2,majorDimension=ROWS` then `[[1,2],[3,4]]`
will set `A1=1,B1=2,A2=3,B2=4`. With `range=A1:B2,majorDimension=COLUMNS`
then `[[1,2],[3,4]]` will set `A1=1,B1=3,A2=2,B2=4`.

When writing, if this field is not set, it defaults to ROWS.

fields.description: The message part body for this part, which may be empty for container MIME message parts.

fields.name: filename
fields.description: The filename of the attachment. Only present if this message part represents an attachment.

fields.name: headers
fields.description: List of headers on this message part. For the top-level message part, representing the entire message payload, it will contain the standard RFC 2822 email headers such as To, From, and Subject.

fields.name: mimeType
fields.description: The MIME type of the message part.

fields.name: partId
fields.description: The immutable ID of the message part.

fields.name: parts
fields.description: The child MIME message parts of this part. This only applies to container MIME message parts, for example multipart/*. For non- container MIME message part types, such as text/plain, this field is empty. For more information, see RFC 1521.

fields.name: historyId
fields.description: The ID of the last history record that modified this message.

fields.name: id
fields.description: The immutable ID of the message.

fields.name: internalDate
fields.description: The internal message creation timestamp (epoch ms), which determines ordering in the inbox. For normal SMTP-received email, this represents the time the message was originally accepted by Google, which is more reliable than the Date header. However, for API-migrated mail, it can be configured by client to be based on the Date header.

fields.name: labelIds
fields.description: List of IDs of labels applied to this message.

fields.name: payload
fields.description: The parsed email structure in the message parts.

fields.name: raw
fields.description: The entire email message in an RFC 2822 formatted and base64url encoded string. Returned in messages.get and drafts.get responses when the format=RAW parameter is supplied.

fields.name: sizeEstimate
fields.description: Estimated size in bytes of the message.

fields.name: snippet
fields.description: A short part of the message text.

fields.name: threadId
fields.description:
The ID of the thread the message belongs to. To add a message or draft to a thread, the following criteria must be met:
- The requested threadId must be specified on the Message or Draft.Message you supply with your request.
- The References and In-Reply-To headers must be set in compliance with the RFC 2822 standard.
- The Subject headers must match.

fields.name: messages
fields.description: List of messages.

fields.name: nextPageToken
fields.description: Token to retrieve the next page of results in the list.

fields.name: resultSizeEstimate
fields.description: Estimated total number of results.

fields.name: key
fields.description: Key for the metadata entry. Keys must conform to the following regexp: [a-zA-Z0-9-_]+, and be less than 128 bytes in length. This is reflected as part of a URL in the metadata server. Additionally, to avoid ambiguity, keys must not conflict with any other metadata keys for the project.

fields.name: value
fields.description: Value for the metadata entry. These are free-form strings, and only have meaning as interpreted by the image running in the instance. The only restriction placed on values is that their size must be less than or equal to 262144 bytes (256 KiB).

fields.name: fingerprint
fields.description: Specifies a fingerprint for this request, which is essentially a hash of the metadata's contents and used for optimistic locking. The fingerprint is initially generated by Compute Engine and changes after every request to modify or update metadata. You must always provide an up-to-date fingerprint hash in order to update or change metadata.

fields.name: items
fields.description: Array of key/value pairs. The total size of all keys and values must be less than 512 KB.

fields.name: kind
fields.description: [Output Only] Type of the resource. Always compute#metadata for metadata.

fields.name: ipCidrRange
fields.description: The IP CIDR range represented by this alias IP range. This IP CIDR range must belong to the specified subnetwork and cannot contain IP addresses reserved by system or used by other network interfaces. This range may be a single IP address (e.g. 10.2.3.4), a netmask (e.g. /24) or a CIDR format string (e.g. 10.1.2.0/24).

fields.name: subnetworkRangeName
fields.description: Optional subnetwork secondary range name specifying the secondary range from which to allocate the IP CIDR range for this alias IP range. If left unspecified, the primary range of the subnetwork will be used.

fields.name: kind
fields.description: [Output Only] Type of the resource. Always compute#accessConfig for access configs.

fields.name: name
fields.description: The name of this access configuration. The default and recommended name is External NAT but you can use any arbitrary string you would like. For example, My external IP or Network Access.

fields.name: natIP
fields.description: An external IP address associated with this instance. Specify an unused static external IP address available to the project or leave this field undefined to use an IP from a shared ephemeral IP address pool. If you specify a static external IP address, it must live in the same region as the zone of the instance.

fields.name: googleType
fields.description: The type of configuration. The default and only option is ONE_TO_ONE_NAT.

fields.name: accessConfigs
fields.description: An array of configurations for this interface. Currently, only one access config, ONE_TO_ONE_NAT, is supported. If there are no accessConfigs specified, then this instance will have no external internet access.

fields.name: aliasIpRanges
fields.description: An array of alias IP ranges for this network interface. Can only be specified for network interfaces on subnet-mode networks.

fields.name: kind
fields.description: [Output Only] Type of the resource. Always compute#networkInterface for network interfaces.

fields.name: name
fields.description: [Output Only] The name of the network interface, generated by the server. For network devices, these are eth0, eth1, etc.

fields.name: network
fields.description:
URL of the network resource for this instance. When creating an instance, if neither the network nor the subnetwork is specified, the default network global/networks/default is used; if the network is not specified but the subnetwork is specified, the network is inferred.

This field is optional when creating a firewall rule. If not specified when creating a firewall rule, the default network global/networks/default is used.

If you specify this property, you can specify the network as a full or partial URL. For example, the following are all valid URLs:
- https://www.googleapis.com/compute/v1/projects/project/global/networks/network
- projects/project/global/networks/network
- global/networks/default

fields.name: networkIP
fields.description: An IPv4 internal network address to assign to the instance for this network interface. If not specified by the user, an unused internal IP is assigned by the system.

fields.name: subnetwork
fields.description:
The URL of the Subnetwork resource for this instance. If the network resource is in legacy mode, do not provide this property. If the network is in auto subnet mode, providing the subnetwork is optional. If the network is in custom subnet mode, then this field should be specified. If you specify this property, you can specify the subnetwork as a full or partial URL. For example, the following are all valid URLs:
- https://www.googleapis.com/compute/v1/projects/project/regions/region/subnetworks/subnetwork
- regions/region/subnetworks/subnetwork

fields.name: headerColor
fields.description:
The color of the first row or column. If this field is set, the first
row or column will be filled with this color and the colors will
alternate between first_band_color and second_band_color starting
from the second row or column. Otherwise, the first row or column will be
filled with first_band_color and the colors will proceed to alternate
as they normally would.

fields.name: firstBandColor
fields.description: The first color that is alternating. (Required)

fields.name: secondBandColor
fields.description: The second color that is alternating. (Required)

fields.name: footerColor
fields.description:
The color of the last row or column. If this field is not set, the last
row or column will be filled with either first_band_color or
second_band_color, depending on the color of the previous row or
column.

fields.name: range
fields.description: The range over which these properties are applied.

fields.name: bandedRangeId
fields.description: The id of the banded range.

fields.name: columnProperties
fields.description:
Properties for column bands. These properties will be applied on a column-
by-column basis throughout all the columns in the range. At least one of
row_properties or column_properties must be specified.

fields.name: rowProperties
fields.description:
Properties for row bands. These properties will be applied on a row-by-row
basis throughout all the rows in the range. At least one of
row_properties or column_properties must be specified.

fields.name: hiddenByUser
fields.description: True if this dimension is explicitly hidden.

fields.name: hiddenByFilter
fields.description:
True if this dimension is being filtered.
This field is read-only.

fields.name: pixelSize
fields.description: The height (if a row) or width (if a column) of the dimension in pixels.

fields.name: startIndex
fields.description: The character index where this run starts.

fields.name: format
fields.description: The format of this run.  Absent values inherit the cell's format.

fields.name: strict
fields.description: True if invalid data should be rejected.

fields.name: inputMessage
fields.description: A message to show the user when adding data to the cell.

fields.name: condition
fields.description: The condition that data in the cell must match.

fields.name: showCustomUi
fields.description:
True if the UI should be customized based on the kind of condition.
If true, "List" conditions will show a dropdown.

fields.name: sourceColumnOffset
fields.description:
The column offset of the source range that this value reads from.

For example, if the source was `C10:E15`, a `sourceColumnOffset` of `0`
means this value refers to column `C`, whereas the offset `1` would
refer to column `D`.

fields.name: name
fields.description:
A name to use for the value. This is only used if formula was set.
Otherwise, the column name is used.

fields.name: formula
fields.description:
A custom formula to calculate the value.  The formula must start
with an `=` character.

fields.name: summarizeFunction
fields.description:
A function to summarize the value.
If formula is set, the only supported values are
SUM and
CUSTOM.
If sourceColumnOffset is set, then `CUSTOM`
is not supported.

fields.name: value
fields.description:
The calculated value the metadata corresponds to.
(Note that formulaValue is not valid,
 because the values will be calculated.)

fields.name: collapsed
fields.description: True if the data corresponding to the value is collapsed.

fields.name: googleType
fields.description: The type of error.

fields.name: message
fields.description:
A message with more information about the error
(in the spreadsheet's locale).

fields.name: formulaValue
fields.description: Represents a formula.

fields.name: boolValue
fields.description: Represents a boolean value.

fields.name: stringValue
fields.description:
Represents a string value.
Leading single quotes are not included. For example, if the user typed
`'123` into the UI, this would be represented as a `stringValue` of
`"123"`.

fields.name: numberValue
fields.description:
Represents a double value.
Note: Dates, Times and DateTimes are represented as doubles in
"serial number" format.

fields.name: errorValue
fields.description:
Represents an error.
This field is read-only.

fields.name: valuesIndex
fields.description:
The offset in the PivotTable.values list which the values in this
grouping should be sorted by.

fields.name: buckets
fields.description:
Determines the bucket from which values are chosen to sort.

For example, in a pivot table with one row group & two column groups,
the row group can list up to two values. The first value corresponds
to a value within the first column group, and the second value
corresponds to a value in the second column group.  If no values
are listed, this would indicate that the row should be sorted according
to the "Grand Total" over the column groups. If a single value is listed,
this would correspond to using the "Total" of that bucket.

fields.name: valueBucket
fields.description:
The bucket of the opposite pivot group to sort by.
If not specified, sorting is alphabetical by this group's values.

fields.name: valueMetadata
fields.description: Metadata about values in the grouping.

fields.name: showTotals
fields.description: True if the pivot table should include the totals for this grouping.

fields.name: sourceColumnOffset
fields.description:
The column offset of the source range that this grouping is based on.

For example, if the source was `C10:E15`, a `sourceColumnOffset` of `0`
means this group refers to column `C`, whereas the offset `1` would refer
to column `D`.

fields.name: sortOrder
fields.description: The order the values in this group should be sorted.

fields.name: visibleValues
fields.description: Values that should be included.  Values not listed here are excluded.

fields.name: criteria
fields.description:
An optional mapping of filters per source column offset.

The filters will be applied before aggregating data into the pivot table.
The map's key is the column offset of the source range that you want to
filter, and the value is the criteria for that column.

For example, if the source was `C10:E15`, a key of `0` will have the filter
for column `C`, whereas the key `1` is for column `D`.

fields.name: rows
fields.description: Each row grouping in the pivot table.

fields.name: valueLayout
fields.description:
Whether values should be listed horizontally (as columns)
or vertically (as rows).

fields.name: values
fields.description: A list of values to include in the pivot table.

fields.name: source
fields.description: The range the pivot table is reading data from.

fields.name: columns
fields.description: Each column grouping in the pivot table.

fields.name: pivotTable
fields.description:
A pivot table anchored at this cell. The size of pivot table itself
is computed dynamically based on its data, grouping, filters, values,
etc. Only the top-left cell of the pivot table contains the pivot table
definition. The other cells will contain the calculated values of the
results of the pivot in their effective_value fields.

fields.name: userEnteredFormat
fields.description:
The format the user entered for the cell.

When writing, the new format will be merged with the existing format.

fields.name: note
fields.description: Any note on the cell.

fields.name: effectiveFormat
fields.description:
The effective format being used by the cell.
This includes the results of applying any conditional formatting and,
if the cell contains a formula, the computed number format.
If the effective format is the default format, effective format will
not be written.
This field is read-only.

fields.name: userEnteredValue
fields.description:
The value the user entered in the cell. e.g, `1234`, `'Hello'`, or `=NOW()`
Note: Dates, Times and DateTimes are represented as doubles in
serial number format.

fields.name: dataValidation
fields.description:
A data validation rule on the cell, if any.

When writing, the new data validation rule will overwrite any prior rule.

fields.name: effectiveValue
fields.description:
The effective value of the cell. For cells with formulas, this will be
the calculated value.  For cells with literals, this will be
the same as the user_entered_value.
This field is read-only.

fields.name: textFormatRuns
fields.description:
Runs of rich text applied to subsections of the cell.  Runs are only valid
on user entered strings, not formulas, bools, or numbers.
Runs start at specific indexes in the text and continue until the next
run. Properties of a run will continue unless explicitly changed
in a subsequent run (and properties of the first run will continue
the properties of the cell unless explicitly changed).

When writing, the new runs will overwrite any prior runs.  When writing a
new user_entered_value, previous runs will be erased.

fields.name: formattedValue
fields.description:
The formatted value of the cell.
This is the value as it's shown to the user.
This field is read-only.

fields.name: hyperlink
fields.description:
A hyperlink this cell points to, if any.
This field is read-only.  (To set it, use a `=HYPERLINK` formula
in the userEnteredValue.formulaValue
field.)

fields.name: values
fields.description: The values in the row, one per column.

fields.name: rowData
fields.description:
The data in the grid, one entry per row,
starting with the row in startRow.
The values in RowData will correspond to columns starting
at start_column.

fields.name: startRow
fields.description: The first row this GridData refers to, zero-based.

fields.name: columnMetadata
fields.description:
Metadata about the requested columns in the grid, starting with the column
in start_column.

fields.name: startColumn
fields.description: The first column this GridData refers to, zero-based.

fields.name: rowMetadata
fields.description:
Metadata about the requested rows in the grid, starting with the row
in start_row.

fields.name: criteria
fields.description:
The criteria for showing/hiding values per column.
The map's key is the column index, and the value is the criteria for
that column.

fields.name: range
fields.description: The range the filter covers.

fields.name: sortSpecs
fields.description:
The sort order per column. Later specifications are used when values
are equal in the earlier specifications.

fields.name: users
fields.description: The email addresses of users with edit access to the protected range.

fields.name: domainUsersCanEdit
fields.description:
True if anyone in the document's domain has edit access to the protected
range.  Domain protection is only supported on documents within a domain.

fields.name: groups
fields.description: The email addresses of groups with edit access to the protected range.

fields.name: description
fields.description: The description of this protected range.

fields.name: unprotectedRanges
fields.description:
The list of unprotected ranges within a protected sheet.
Unprotected ranges are only supported on protected sheets.

fields.name: namedRangeId
fields.description:
The named range this protected range is backed by, if any.

When writing, only one of range or named_range_id
may be set.

fields.name: protectedRangeId
fields.description:
The ID of the protected range.
This field is read-only.

fields.name: warningOnly
fields.description:
True if this protected range will show a warning when editing.
Warning-based protection means that every user can edit data in the
protected range, except editing will prompt a warning asking the user
to confirm the edit.

When writing: if this field is true, then editors is ignored.
Additionally, if this field is changed from true to false and the
`editors` field is not set (nor included in the field mask), then
the editors will be set to all the editors in the document.

fields.name: requestingUserCanEdit
fields.description:
True if the user who requested this protected range can edit the
protected area.
This field is read-only.

fields.name: range
fields.description:
The range that is being protected.
The range may be fully unbounded, in which case this is considered
a protected sheet.

When writing, only one of range or named_range_id
may be set.

fields.name: editors
fields.description:
The users and groups with edit access to the protected range.
This field is only visible to users with edit access to the protected
range and the document.
Editors are not supported with warning_only protection.

fields.name: color
fields.description: The color this interpolation point should use.

fields.name: googleType
fields.description: How the value should be interpreted.

fields.name: value
fields.description:
The value this interpolation point uses.  May be a formula.
Unused if type is MIN or
MAX.

fields.name: midpoint
fields.description: An optional midway interpolation point.

fields.name: maxpoint
fields.description: The final interpolation point.

fields.name: minpoint
fields.description: The starting interpolation point.

fields.name: condition
fields.description:
The condition of the rule. If the condition evaluates to true,
the format will be applied.

fields.name: format
fields.description:
The format to apply.
Conditional formatting can only apply a subset of formatting:
bold, italic,
strikethrough,
foreground color &
background color.

fields.name: booleanRule
fields.description: The formatting is either "on" or "off" according to the rule.

fields.name: ranges
fields.description:
The ranges that will be formatted if the condition is true.
All the ranges must be on the same grid.

fields.name: gradientRule
fields.description: The formatting will vary based on the gradients in the rule.

fields.name: dimensionIndex
fields.description: The dimension the sort should be applied to.

fields.name: sortOrder
fields.description: The order data should be sorted.

fields.name: userEnteredValue
fields.description:
A value the condition is based on.
The value will be parsed as if the user typed into a cell.
Formulas are supported (and must begin with an `=`).

fields.name: relativeDate
fields.description:
A relative date (based on the current date).
Valid only if the type is
DATE_BEFORE,
DATE_AFTER,
DATE_ON_OR_BEFORE or
DATE_ON_OR_AFTER.

Relative dates are not supported in data validation.
They are supported only in conditional formatting and
conditional filters.

fields.name: values
fields.description:
The values of the condition. The number of supported values depends
on the condition type.  Some support zero values,
others one or two values,
and ConditionType.ONE_OF_LIST supports an arbitrary number of values.

fields.name: googleType
fields.description: The type of condition.

fields.name: condition
fields.description:
A condition that must be true for values to be shown.
(This does not override hiddenValues -- if a value is listed there,
 it will still be hidden.)

fields.name: hiddenValues
fields.description: Values that should be hidden.

fields.name: filterViewId
fields.description: The ID of the filter view.

fields.name: criteria
fields.description:
The criteria for showing/hiding values per column.
The map's key is the column index, and the value is the criteria for
that column.

fields.name: title
fields.description: The name of the filter view.

fields.name: range
fields.description:
The range this filter view covers.

When writing, only one of range or named_range_id
may be set.

fields.name: sortSpecs
fields.description:
The sort order per column. Later specifications are used when values
are equal in the earlier specifications.

fields.name: namedRangeId
fields.description:
The named range this filter view is backed by, if any.

When writing, only one of range or named_range_id
may be set.

fields.name: bubbleMaxRadiusSize
fields.description:
The max radius size of the bubbles, in pixels.
If specified, the field must be a positive value.

fields.name: series
fields.description:
The data contianing the bubble y-values.  These values locate the bubbles
in the chart vertically.

fields.name: legendPosition
fields.description: Where the legend of the chart should be drawn.

fields.name: domain
fields.description:
The data containing the bubble x-values.  These values locate the bubbles
in the chart horizontally.

fields.name: bubbleSizes
fields.description:
The data contianing the bubble sizes.  Bubble sizes are used to draw
the bubbles at different sizes relative to each other.
If specified, group_ids must also be specified.  This field is
optional.

fields.name: bubbleOpacity
fields.description:
The opacity of the bubbles between 0 and 1.0.
0 is fully transparent and 1 is fully opaque.

fields.name: bubbleBorderColor
fields.description: The bubble border color.

fields.name: bubbleTextStyle
fields.description:
The format of the text inside the bubbles.
Underline and Strikethrough are not supported.

fields.name: groupIds
fields.description:
The data containing the bubble group IDs. All bubbles with the same group
ID will be drawn in the same color. If bubble_sizes is specified then
this field must also be specified but may contain blank values.
This field is optional.

fields.name: bubbleLabels
fields.description: The data containing the bubble labels.  These do not need to be unique.

fields.name: bubbleMinRadiusSize
fields.description:
The minimum radius size of the bubbles, in pixels.
If specific, the field must be a positive value.

fields.name: reversed
fields.description: True to reverse the order of the domain values (horizontal axis).

fields.name: data
fields.description: The data of the CandlestickDomain.

fields.name: data
fields.description: The data of the CandlestickSeries.

fields.name: openSeries
fields.description:
The range data (vertical axis) for the open/initial value for each
candle. This is the bottom of the candle body.  If less than the close
value the candle will be filled.  Otherwise the candle will be hollow.

fields.name: highSeries
fields.description:
The range data (vertical axis) for the high/maximum value for each
candle. This is the top of the candle's center line.

fields.name: closeSeries
fields.description:
The range data (vertical axis) for the close/final value for each candle.
This is the top of the candle body.  If greater than the open value the
candle will be filled.  Otherwise the candle will be hollow.

fields.name: lowSeries
fields.description:
The range data (vertical axis) for the low/minimum value for each candle.
This is the bottom of the candle's center line.

fields.name: data
fields.description:
The Candlestick chart data.
Only one CandlestickData is supported.

fields.name: domain
fields.description:
The domain data (horizontal axis) for the candlestick chart.  String data
will be treated as discrete labels, other data will be treated as
continuous values.

fields.name: barColor
fields.description:
The color of the column representing this series in each bucket.
This field is optional.

fields.name: data
fields.description: The data for this histogram series.

fields.name: bucketSize
fields.description:
By default the bucket size (the range of values stacked in a single
column) is chosen automatically, but it may be overridden here.
E.g., A bucket size of 1.5 results in buckets from 0 - 1.5, 1.5 - 3.0, etc.
Cannot be negative.
This field is optional.

fields.name: outlierPercentile
fields.description:
The outlier percentile is used to ensure that outliers do not adversely
affect the calculation of bucket sizes.  For example, setting an outlier
percentile of 0.05 indicates that the top and bottom 5% of values when
calculating buckets.  The values are still included in the chart, they will
be added to the first or last buckets instead of their own buckets.
Must be between 0.0 and 0.5.

fields.name: showItemDividers
fields.description:
Whether horizontal divider lines should be displayed between items in each
column.

fields.name: series
fields.description:
The series for a histogram may be either a single series of values to be
bucketed or multiple series, each of the same length, containing the name
of the series followed by the values to be bucketed for that series.

fields.name: legendPosition
fields.description: The position of the chart legend.

fields.name: threeDimensional
fields.description: True if the pie is three dimensional.

fields.name: domain
fields.description: The data that covers the domain of the pie chart.

fields.name: series
fields.description: The data that covers the one and only series of the pie chart.

fields.name: pieHole
fields.description: The size of the hole in the pie chart.

fields.name: legendPosition
fields.description: Where the legend of the pie chart should be drawn.

fields.name: tooltips
fields.description:
The data containing the tooltip for the corresponding node.  A blank value
results in no tooltip being displayed for the node.
This field is optional.

fields.name: selectedNodeColor
fields.description: The color of the selected org chart nodes.

fields.name: parentLabels
fields.description:
The data containing the label of the parent for the corresponding node.
A blank value indicates that the node has no parent and is a top-level
node.
This field is optional.

fields.name: labels
fields.description:
The data containing the labels for all the nodes in the chart.  Labels
must be unique.

fields.name: nodeSize
fields.description: The size of the org chart nodes.

fields.name: nodeColor
fields.description: The color of the org chart nodes.

fields.name: reversed
fields.description: True to reverse the order of the domain values (horizontal axis).

fields.name: domain
fields.description:
The data of the domain. For example, if charting stock prices over time,
this is the data representing the dates.

fields.name: sources
fields.description:
The ranges of data for a series or domain.
Exactly one dimension must have a length of 1,
and all sources in the list must have the same dimension
with length 1.
The domain (if it exists) & all series must have the same number
of source ranges. If using more than one source range, then the source
range at a given offset must be contiguous across the domain and series.

For example, these are valid configurations:

    domain sources: A1:A5
    series1 sources: B1:B5
    series2 sources: D6:D10

    domain sources: A1:A5, C10:C12
    series1 sources: B1:B5, D10:D12
    series2 sources: C1:C5, E10:E12

fields.name: sourceRange
fields.description: The source ranges of the data.

fields.name: googleType
fields.description:
The type of this series. Valid only if the
chartType is
COMBO.
Different types will change the way the series is visualized.
Only LINE, AREA,
and COLUMN are supported.

fields.name: series
fields.description: The data being visualized in this chart series.

fields.name: targetAxis
fields.description:
The minor axis that will specify the range of values for this series.
For example, if charting stocks over time, the "Volume" series
may want to be pinned to the right with the prices pinned to the left,
because the scale of trading volume is different than the scale of

A thumbnail resource identifies different thumbnail image sizes associated with a resource. Please note the following characteristics of thumbnail images:

A thumbnail resource identifies different thumbnail image sizes associated with a resource. Please note the following characteristics of thumbnail images:

A resource's snippet.thumbnails property is an object that identifies the thumbnail images available for that resource.
A thumbnail resource contains a series of objects. The name of each object (default, medium, high, etc.) refers to the thumbnail image size.
Different types of resources may support different thumbnail image sizes.
Different types of resources may define different sizes for thumbnail images with the same name. For example, the default thumbnail image for a video resource is typically 120px by 90px, and the default thumbnail image for a channel resource is typically 88px by 88px.
Resources of the same type may still have different thumbnail image sizes for certain images depending on the resolution of the original image or content uploaded to Youtube. For example, an HD video may support higher resolution thumbnails than non-HD videos.
Each object that contains information about a thumbnail image size has a width property and a height property. However, the width and height properties may not be returned for that image.
If an uploaded thumbnail image does not match the required dimensions, the image is resized to match the correct size without changing its aspect ratio. The image is not cropped, but may include black bars so that the size is correct.
